snippet.textDisplay: On Chris' car- the sudden blowby and resultant loss of compression could have been a "corn starch cocktail"; an old quick fix for a car with tired rings or blowby was to spoon dry powder cornstatch into the carb at about 2500 rpm- it would create a temporary glaze on the cylinder walls, making the blowby seem to go away. This would have let the car run strong for a bit, but under the final racing conditions it would have crisped and blown out the exhaust- leaving Chris with a blown motor. Just a thought from somebody who bought a car that had been "corn starched".

snippet.textDisplay:
This will sound insane, but you were shifting too late.
Not only will the short shift keep the tires on the ground but you can actually get a better time if your blow-off valve isn't dumping pressure.
You want to wind it up to the edge of pressure and then shift before it pops.
You want to get into top gear as soon as feasible. I think if you had a few months to practice you could get it into 11s
